title: Getting Started
text: Tensors used machine deep learning multi-dimensional array structures. addition space efficient provide common framework automatic differentiation, engine deep neural network training. packages, notably R interfaces tensorflow keras, use native R structures tensor storage, form vectors (1-dimentional arrays), matrices (2 dimensions), higher dimensional arrays. Tensors usually represent “set ” relationships. example, vector like point <- c(20.2, 19.1, 24.8) might represent 1-dimensional tensor storing point space X, Y, Z coordinate values. matrix form points <- matrix(runif(10*3), ncol = 3, nrow = 10) represent 10 points, points[6, ] accessing sixth. However, tensors often referred “dimensionality” avoid confusing array dimensions data dimensions; rather, ’d call point (1-d array) “rank 1 tensor” matrix points (2-d array) “rank 2 tensor”. hand, common refer specific “dimensions” array “axes” (Python’s numpy refers axes multidimensional arrays example). TidyTensor eschews well favor rank-based nomenclature; rather referring first second axes points (slicing data point spatial coordinate respectively), ’ll refer first second ranks. Tensors also shape, conveniently returned R’s dim() function. point tensor shape (3) (parentheses used denote shape vector) points shape (10, 3).

code: images[1:4, , , ] %>%   tt() %>%   set_ranknames(image, row, col, channel) %>%   permute(image, channel, row, col) %>%   set_dimnames_for_rank(channel, R, G, B) %>%   as.data.frame() %>%   head() image channel row col value 1     1       R   1   1    59 2     2       R   1   1   154 3     3       R   1   1   255 4     4       R   1   1    28 5     1       G   1   1    62 6     2       G   1   1   177 images[1:4, , , ] %>%   tt() %>%   set_ranknames(image, row, col, channel) %>%   permute(image, channel, row, col) %>%   set_dimnames_for_rank(channel, R, G, B) %>%   as.data.frame() %>%   ggplot() +     geom_tile(aes(x = col, y = row, fill = value)) +     facet_grid(channel ~ image) +     coord_equal() library(tidyr)  images[1:4, , , ] %>%   tt() %>%   set_ranknames(image, row, col, channel) %>%   permute(image, channel, row, col) %>%   set_dimnames_for_rank(channel, R, G, B) %>%   as.data.frame() %>%   spread(channel, value) %>%   ggplot() +     geom_tile(aes(x = col, y = row, fill = rgb(R, G, B, maxColorValue = 255))) +     facet_wrap( ~ image) +     coord_equal() +     scale_y_reverse() +     scale_fill_identity() vgg_model <- application_vgg16(include_top = FALSE, input_shape = c(32, 32, 3))  input <- vgg_model$input output <- get_layer(vgg_model, name = "block1_conv2")$output  # input shape (N, 32, 32, 3) # output shape (N, 32, 32, 64) tensor, where last rank are feature maps compute_featuremaps <- k_function(input, output) library(dplyr)  compute_featuremaps(images[1:4, , ,]) %>%    tt() %>%   set_ranknames(image, row, col, featuremap) %>%   as.data.frame(allow_huge = T) %>%   filter(featuremap <= 6) %>%   ggplot() +     geom_tile(aes(x = col, y = row, fill = value)) +     facet_grid(image ~ featuremap) +     coord_equal() +     scale_y_reverse()

title: TidyTensor
text: Finally tt_apply(), tidytensor’s answer base-R apply(), another area -greatness arrays R. apply() allows applying arbitrary ranks MARGIN parameter, removes metadata, deconstructs call’s return value vector, prepending remaining ranks. t shape (500, 3, 26, 26) normalize function returns array shape ’s input, apply(t, MARGIN = c(1, 2), normalize) doesn’t return tensor shape t, rather shape c(26 * 26, 500, 3). Blech. tt_apply() uses apply() hood, puts pieces back together nicely (rankname-aware function inputs outputs). However, tt_apply() limited compared apply() one respect, applies “top” N ranks, stick sets--sets metaphor. t ranknames c("image", "channel", "row", "col"), can tt_apply() every image, every channel (within image), every row (within channel within image), . different grouping desired, permute() can help. ’s normalize() function respects metadata input tidytensors (R functions , [], apply(), scale() notable exceptions). pre-processing, rather scale entire dataset [0,1] range, perhaps ’d like channel image, maximizing dynamic range utilized (perhaps actually useful model training!). Notice ’ve organized data channel-first can per-image, per-channel normalization, permuted back original. Even though tt_apply() built base-R apply(), applying can take time, function call executed entry asked can quite large tensor. function call results needn’t match input shape: tt_apply() just needs returned result tensors (vectors, matrices, arrays, tidytensors) shape. featuremap example difficult visualize due range map values; can get alternative look scaling zero mean, one variance per featuremap. (perhaps build model batch-normalization!)
code: # scales to [0, 1] normalize <- function(t) {   t <- t - min(t)   t <- t / max(t)   return(t) } images_normalized <- images %>%   permute(image, channel, row, col) %>%   # permute to channels-first   tt_apply(channel, normalize) %>%        # normalize each (row, col) tensor   permute(image, row, col, channel)       # permute back if we want images <- dataset_cifar10()$train$x %>%   tt() %>%    set_ranknames(image, row, col, channel) %>%   set_dimnames_for_rank(channel, R, G, B)    library(dplyr)   # for filter() library(ggplot2)    images %>%    subset(image = 1:4) %>%   compute_featuremaps() %>%   tt() %>%   set_ranknames(image, row, col, featuremap) %>%   permute(image, featuremap, row, col) %>%   tt_apply(featuremap, function(t) {     (t - mean(t)) / sd(t)   }) %>%   as.data.frame() %>%   filter(featuremap <= 6) %>%   ggplot() +     geom_tile(aes(x = col, y = row, fill = value)) +     facet_grid(image ~ featuremap) +     coord_equal() +     scale_y_reverse() +     scale_fill_gradient2()
